 The Glock is a wonderful gun...we all know that. But some of the parts should be changed to improve performance. This part is more than 50% heavier than the factory plastic part which will help you shoot the gun faster and more accurately because it reduces recoil and muzzle flip.

Alright guys here's the deal.

I picked this up off an AK collecter that was moving and needed extra funds. This is a standard Legion/Arsenal marked SGL21, but with a tasteful addition.

The rifle was sent to a reputable AK builder in Vegas to get the Bulgarian triangle folder treatment. They Installed a 4.5mm Bulgy trunnion and folding stock; everything looks stupendous. Just like the factory SLRs. Also included is the GRIP REINFORCEMENT PLATE which is VERY hard to come by and almost a necessity for folding SGLs. Look up Jim Fuller of Rifle Dynamics. Great work on AKs.

Barrel is clean, no pitting or rough spots. None of the furniture is canted, but there are some very light "handling" marks that you really have to look for. With my experience of AKs and specifically Saiga rifles, it looks like it had a max of 200 rounds fired through it. I'm looking at the bolt, hammer, rail paint wear, and carbon on the piston head (barely any). 

I know this thing's value, and how much they go for on the forums so please, no stupid offers. You won't hear a reply from me.

postcontent: For sale is a new Kel-Tec PMR-30 chambered in .22 WMR. The PMR-30 is a light weight, full size pistol chambered for the flat-shooting .22Magnum cartridge (.22WMR). The PMR-30 operates on a unique hybrid blowback/locked-breech system. This operation system allows for the use of a wide variety of ammunition as it seamlessly adjusts between locked breech and blowback operation, depending on the pressure of the cartridge. It uses a double stack magazine of a new design that holds 30 rounds and fits completely in the grip of the pistol. The trigger is a crisp single action with an over-travel stop. The manual safety is a thumb activated ambidextrous safety lever (up for SAFE, down for FIRE). The slide locks back after the last shot and a manual slide lock lever is also provided. The light, crisp trigger pull and fiber optic sights make the PMR-30 ideal for target shooting and hunting small game.

Whether you’re slugging it out in wet New England grouse cover or a scorching hot dove field south of the border, you won’t have to worry about the Ultra Light’s beautiful walnut stock. Both the stock and fore-end are sealed with a five-step process called WeatherCoat. This new coating makes it impervious to any kind of weather and as a bonus, this special stock finishing process also enhances the fancy figure of the wood. No matter if you’re in those long pheasant fields in South Dakota or after scaled quail running through the cactus, if your average hunting day is measured in miles.

title: For Sale:  Remington 700 SPS Tactical in .223
postcontent:
I've got a Remington 700 SPS Tactical in .223 that I'm looking to sell because we've already got way too many rifles in that caliber.

It's got a fairly low round count, Hogue Overmolded pillar-bedded stock, and 1:9 barrel twist rate that can handle at least up to a 70 grain bullet. Barrel length is 20" and it has a heavy target profile, production date should be 2008/early 2009 so it's better quality than most newer SPS models I've seen. Shoots sub-MOA with 69gr JHPBT handloads and close to that with good commercial ammo, I haven't chronographed it but data I found from another test shows a 20" Rem 700 will push a Federal 55gr at about 3,300 FPS and Black Hills 68gr match ammo at roughly 2,800.

Very handy but capable package, asking $475. I live in Lincoln County, MO and would be willing to drive 30 miles or so to meet up.
